  "prompt": "How is RMM calculated in chemistry?",
  "response": "In chemistry, RMM stands for Relative Molecular Mass, which is often abbreviated as Mr. It is a measure used to compare the mass of a molecule to one twelfth the mass of an atom of carbon-12, which is defined as exactly 12 atomic mass units (amu). The RMM is effectively the sum of the relative atomic masses of all the atoms present in a molecule. Here\u2019s how you can calculate it:\n\n1. **Identify the Molecular Formula**: Determine the molecular formula of the compound for which you want to calculate the RMM. This formula indicates the number and type of atoms present in the molecule.\n\n2. **Find Atomic Masses**: Obtain the relative atomic masses (Ar) of each element present in the molecule. These values are typically found on the periodic table and are usually expressed in atomic mass units (amu).\n\n3. **Multiply by Number of Atoms**: For each element in the molecule, multiply the relative atomic mass by the number of atoms of that element within the molecule. \n\n4. **Sum Up the Values**: Add together all the values obtained in the previous step to get the total relative molecular mass of the molecule.\n\nFor example, to calculate the RMM of water (H\u2082O):\n- Hydrogen (H) has an Ar of approximately 1 amu. Since there are 2 hydrogen atoms, their total contribution is 2 x 1 = 2 amu.\n- Oxygen (O) has an Ar of approximately 16 amu, and there is 1 oxygen atom, so its contribution is 16 amu.\n\nThe RMM of water is therefore 2 + 16 = 18 amu.\n\nOverall, RMM allows chemists to compare the masses of different molecules in a standardized way based on the atomic mass scale.",
